ters I00413 and I00414, and then through them to the Cowles descendants of the next generation."},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"X02778","date_year":1822,"date_month":10,"date_day":22,"location_city":"Cayuga","location_county":"Cayuga County","location_state":"New York","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death","end_year":1861,"children_ids":["I00413","I00414"]}],"education":[],"career":[{"title":"Attorney","dates":"~1820s-1861","type":"law","notes":"Practiced law in the Village of Cayuga, Cayuga County NY."},{"title":"Associate Judge","organization":"Cayuga County Court","type":"law","notes":"Served as Associate Judge in Cayuga County per Baker Family Tree genealogy blog, citing local Cayuga history."},{"title":"Member, New York State Assembly","organization":"New York State Legislature","type":"politics","notes":"Elected to the NY State Assembly 'for a period' per Baker Family Tree genealogy blog. Specific term(s) not yet documented in primary sources."},{"title":"Builder, Hutchinson Homestead","dates":"1822+","type":"civic","notes":"Built the Hutchinson Homestead in the Village of Cayuga on land belonging to his wife Elizabeth. A historical marker at the site notes the original house was burned in 1910."}],"military_service":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"tags":["lawyer","judge","politician"],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Two daughters married two Cowles brothers","body":"Mosley's daughters Elizabeth Caroline (born 1827) and Sarah Frances (born 1837) both married Cowles brothers from the Hooker family line — Edwin Cowles, the Cleveland Leader publisher, and Alfred Cowles, the Chicago Tribune business manager. The double sister-brother exchange tied the Cayuga County Hutchinsons into both branches of the Cowles newspaper empire."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Married a widow with two hundred Cayuga acres","body":"Mosley married Elizabeth Boardman Hall in October 1822. She was a young widow — her first husband John Davis had drowned falling off the Cayuga Lake bridge in 1819 — and came to the marriage with two hundred acres of lake-front land, on which Mosley built what local historians call the Hutchinson Homestead. A historical marker stands on the site today."},{"number":3,"category":"character","header":"Mayflower descent through his mother Betsy Buell","body":"Mosley's mother Elizabeth 'Betsy' Buell (1774-1825) was a documented Mayflower descendant. This ancestry passed through Mosley to his daughters Elizabeth Caroline and Sarah Frances Hutchinson, and from them to their children by Edwin Cowles and Alfred Cowles — adding a Plymouth Colony thread to the broader Hooker-Cowles lineage."}],"quotes":[],"sources":[{"short":"Find a Grave Memorial 92031861","url":"https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/92031861/mosley-hutchinson","accessed":"2026-05"},{"short":"Find a Grave Memorial 92032994 (wife Elizabeth Boardman Hall Hutchinson)","url":"https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/92032994/elizabeth-boardman-hutchinson","accessed":"2026-05"},{"short":"Spared & Shared 4 — 1841 letter Mosley Hutchinson to Elizabeth Boardman Hall Hutchinson","url":"https://sparedshared4.wordpress.com/letters/1841-mosley-hutchinson-to-elizabeth-boardman-hall-hutchinson/","accessed":"2026-05"},{"short":"Baker Family Tree blog — Chapter 14 From the Pilgrims to Today (2007)","url":"http://bakerfamilytree.blogspot.com/2007/10/chapter-14-from-pilgrims-to-today.html","accessed":"2026-05"}],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"slug":"mosley-hutchinson-1796"},"X02778":{"id":"X02778","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"bio":{"first_name":"Elizabeth","middle_name":"Boardman","last_name":"Hutchinson","maiden_name":"Hall","married_names":["Davis","Hutchinson"],"gender":"female","display_name":"Elizabeth Boardman Hall Hutchinson"},"birth":{"year":1801,"month":4,"day":15,"city":"Cayuga","county":"Cayuga County","state":"New York","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"death":{"year":1877,"month":5,"day":28,"city":"Cayuga","county":"Cayuga County","state":"New York","country":"United States"},"residence":{},"burial":{"plot_notes":"Lakeview Cemetery, Village of Cayuga, Cayuga County NY — with husband Mosley Hutchinson and several children (per Find a Grave Memorial 92032994)"},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":true},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"parents":{},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":2,"spouse_id":"X02775","date_year":1822,"date_month":10,"date_day":22,"location_city":"Cayuga","location_county":"Cayuga County","location_state":"New York","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death_of_husband","end_year":1861,"children_ids":["I00413","I00414"]}],"education":[],"career":[],"military_service":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"tags":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Young widow with two hundred Cayuga Lake acres","body":"Elizabeth married Dr. John Davis in February 1818, but he drowned falling off the Cayuga Lake bridge in 1819 — leaving her a widow before twenty, owning two hundred acres of lake-front land. Three years later she married attorney Mosley Hutchinson, and together they built the Hutchinson Homestead that remained a Cayuga landmark until it burned in 1910."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Both daughters married prominent Cowles brothers","body":"Two of Elizabeth and Mosley's daughters — Elizabeth Caroline (born 1827) and Sarah Frances (born 1837) — married the Cowles brothers Edwin and Alfred, who ran the Cleveland Leader and the Chicago Tribune respectively. Elizabeth outlived her husband Mosley by sixteen years, running the homestead until her death at age seventy-six in 1877."}],"quotes":[],"sources":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"slug":"elizabeth-hall-1801"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}